  "prompt": "How were the 7 continents formed?",
  "response": "The formation of the 7 continents is a result of plate tectonics and continental drift over millions of years. Here's a brief overview:\n\n1. Early Earth (4.6 billion years ago):\n- Initially, all land was part of a single supercontinent called Pangaea\n- Surrounded by a single global ocean\n\n2. Breaking of Pangaea (200 million years ago):\n- Pangaea began to break apart due to tectonic plate movements\n- Gradually split into two large landmasses: Laurasia (northern continents) and Gondwana (southern continents)\n\n3. Continued Continental Drift:\n- Tectonic plates continued to move\n- Continents slowly drifted to their current positions\n- Processes like seafloor spreading and subduction caused land masses to separate\n\n4. Current Continental Formation:\n- North America and Europe separated\n- South America and Africa drifted apart\n- India separated from Africa and eventually collided with Asia, forming the Himalayas\n- Australia separated from Antarctica\n\n5. Ongoing Process:\n- Continents are still moving\n- Plates continue to shift, though very slowly (few centimeters per year)\n\nThis process of continental formation took hundreds of millions of years and is based on geological evidence and plate tectonic theory.",
